<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> So.....you're a minion, huh?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.35)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1584'>Zach "yodamuppet" Marshall</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1584&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 22, 2001</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I&#39;m guessing most of you reading this are quite familiar with the game, so this might be old news to you. Then again, a lot of you out there are quite new to the game (myself included), so this is beneficial after all. Well like the description says, I&#39;m going to be covering each of the shadow races, followed up with some card spotlights. I&#39;m hoping that by the end of this article you&#39;ll have a better understanding of each shadow race, and you&#39;ll put that to use when building your next deck. Moving on...<br>
<br>
<br>
Isengard (aka Uruk-hai)<br>
<br>
First up on the list is what I believe to be one of the most balanced shadow races. Don&#39;t believe me? Read on. The Uruk-hai are quite tough, really. The minions themselves have a strength ranging from 5 to 13, with 9 being about average. Their vitality is anywhere from 1 to 4, making them just lively enough to survive all but moderate to heavy archery (or you could play Spies Of Saruman to avoid archery altogether). And the average cost to play one of these little critters is only 3! Okay, that&#39;s all well and good, but what makes them really stand out? Most all of them have Damage +1, meaning that when they win a skirmish, the opposing character takes 2 wounds instead of 1. But wait, there&#39;s more! They have a good assortment of support cards too. Take &#39;Bred For Battle&#39; for example: it plays for free, and all you have to do is exert an Uruk-hai to make him strength +3. Saruman&#39;s Ambition is another good example of a card that can ruin characters when combined with other so-called skirmish buffs. There&#39;s more to skirmish bonuses though. &#39;Wariness&#39; can be a game ender with so many people relying on the stealth of Hobbits to get them to site 9. It just makes it too easy to overwhelm the ring-bearer. This all sounds really great, and I know you&#39;re all psyched out about throwing an Uruk-hai deck together, but there&#39;s a a bit of a drawback to these guys. Until the fellowship reaches site 5, you have roaming costs to worry about. Fortunately for you, the cost of most Uruk-hai minions is quite reasonable. <br>
<br>
Must haves for an Isengard deck:<br>
<br>
*Bred For Battle - as mentioned above, it&#39;s free. And it could mean the difference between causing a wound or overwhelming a character. Certainly fits nicely in the deck.<br>
*Lurtz, Servant of Isengard - it&#39;s like he&#39;s on steroids, plus he&#39;s an archer. Add Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry (which, by the way, can be used with any Uruk-hai) and spot another Uruk-hai to make him a beast. Add insult to injury by making sure he&#39;s got and Uruk-hai Sword in hand.<br>
*Hunt Them Down! - the Uruk&#39;s damage +1 trait is pretty cool, so why not take advantage of it by letting one of your minions attack twice.<br>
*Saruman&#39;s Ambition - I lost a game to this card. If it&#39;s something you can lose to, it&#39;s worth playing in your own deck.<br>
<br>
<br>
Moria (aka those gosh darnited Orcs)<br>
<br>
Ah, yes. The ugly little goons you love to hate but want to play with anyway. They&#39;re all about swarming the opponent, and they do a pretty decent job of it too. If you just want to overwhelm characters, Moria Orcs are a good starting point. With the exception of the Cave Troll, most of these critters play for the small twilight cost of about 2. Their strength ranges from 5 to 15 (none other than the Cave Troll Of Moria there), with an average strength of about 6. Sounds great so far, but as you might have guessed there&#39;s a setback. A good sum of Moria Orcs have a vitality of only 1, leaving them incredibly vulnerable to archery fire. Fortunately for them, and you, there are ways to deal with that. &#39;Goblin Wallcrawler&#39; reduces the fellowship archery total by 1 if you can spot another Moria Orc. Get out four of these guys and you should be quite safe from all but the special abilities of &#39;Legolas, Greenleaf&#39; and &#39;Aragorn&#39;s Bow&#39; during the archery phase, for at least one turn. Or you can play with a few &#39;Pinned Down&#39; and some &#39;Goblin Archer&#39;s, letting you get in a few archery shots while reducing the fellowship archery total at the same time. Though these minions have a site number of 4, their inexpensive twilight cost makes dealing with roaming cost problems practically a thing of the past. Moria Orcs also have a decent selection of support cards, not only for skirmishing but for providing greater opposition for your opponent. Elves seem pretty popular, so why not play with &#39;Through The Misty Mountains&#39; to make the fellowship discard cards for moving through three sites. Or you can try &#39;They Are Coming&#39; to clear dead cards out of your hand and get that &#39;Goblin Scavenger&#39; back in play with a &#39;Goblin Scimitar&#39;. So now you must be aching to build a Moria deck too, huh? <br>
<br>
Must haves for a Moria deck:<br>
<br>
*Cave Troll Of Moria - he&#39;s a beast, plain and simple, and it&#39;s possible to play him for a total twilight cost of only 5. Most site 4&#39;s are underground, and the (currently) only site 5 is underground, so the Cave Troll comes out for -3 already. &#39;Troll&#39;s Keyward&#39; makes the twilight cost of the Cave Troll another -2, so you can toss him out mighty cheap and let him go to town on the fellowship. Add the Cave Troll&#39;s Hammer and a Goblin Scimitar for the Troll&#39;s Keyward, and you&#39;ve got a mean little team for a total twilight cost of 9. <br>
*Goblin Scimitar - this card is too good to be common, in my opinion. It plays for free, and lets you draw another card when you play it. <br>
*Goblin Scavengers - play one of these guys and get back a Goblin Scimitar from your discard pile.<br>
*They Are Coming - good for clearing out your hand and getting back a minion. <br>
*Host Of Thousands - plays for free and lets you play a Moria Orc from your discard pile. Worth playing four, if you don&#39;t mind my saying so.<br>
*Pinned Down - play with a few of these and four Goblin Archers to greatly reduce the number of archery wounds you have to deal with, while at the same time dishing out some of your own.<br>
<br>
<br>
Sauron (aka discarding is a nuisance)<br>
<br>
These folks are a cross-breed of discarding effects and power. They&#39;re not quite the same swarm material as the Moria Orcs, with their site number of 6, but they have a fairly low twilight cost that helps compensate. You can also play with a few &#39;Orc Ambusher&#39;s and &#39;Orc Assassin&#39;s, or &#39;Orc Scouting Band&#39;s to help out with roaming costs if you feel the need. Their biggest feature is their knack for making the fellowship discard cards. &#39;Orc Inquisitor&#39;, &#39;Band Of The Eye&#39;, &#39;Desperate Defense Of The Ring&#39;, &#39;Orc Butchery&#39;, all cards that cause the opponent to discard cards and the list goes on. Of course, most of these discard actions rely on a minion winning a skirmish. But that&#39;s not much of a problem considering the strength of these minions. Their vitality is nothing to brag about, but with an average of 2 they can at least survive archery fire. Most of the support cards for this race deal with discarding cards or adding burdens, but there are a few that add strength to your minions. It&#39;s the conditions and events that work outside of skirmishes (or when skirmishes don&#39;t take place) that impress me most. &#39;Thin And Stretched&#39; is a good example of this. When the ring-bearer isn&#39;t assigned to a skirmish and someone goes in his place, the free peoples player has another burden to deal with. &#39;Under The Watching Eye&#39; is another great card. Every time the fellowship moves, a companion has to exert. That can be quite useful when used in combination with &#39;Hate&#39;. <br>
<br>
Must haves for a Sauron Orc deck:<br>
<br>
*Seeking It Always - with Hobbit decks being quite popular, cancelling a stealth event can win you the game.<br>
*Thin And Stretched - adding burdens is fun! If the free peoples player doesn&#39;t feel they want to add any more burdens, you might have a chance to kill the ring-bearer.<br>
*Band Of The Eye - 12 strength for a twilight cost of only 4 is too good of a deal to pass up. Not to mention the added bonus of making your opponent discard a card at random for losing a skirmish.<br>
*Desperate Defense Of The Ring - This is a great card. Give them out to most or all of your opponent&#39;s fellowship, and they now have to deal with discarding 3 cards per skirmish, or adding a burden. <br>
*Orc War Band - 10 strength for a twilight cost of 4, and you can exert it to wound a companion it skirmishes. <br>
*Under The Watching Eye - every time the fellowship moves, the free peoples player has to exert a companion. And this gem isn&#39;t unique, so you can have multiple copies on the table.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ringwraith (aka nasty Nazgul)<br>
<br>
Last but certainly not least, my favorite shadow race. While they may seem expensive at first, they&#39;re worth the twilight cost. Most have a site number of 3 (some have a site number 2), so roaming isn&#39;t much of a problem early on. They&#39;re undeniably the toughest minion around, with a strength ranging from 9 to 12, and a number of cards boosting them even more. And most all of them are either fierce or have a means to become fierce, so they can take on two characters per turn, or possibly the same character twice. Not to worry about the ever so popular archery either, as these fellas have an average vitality of 3, and you have &#39;All Blades Perish&#39; and &#39;Not Easily Destroyed&#39; to keep them on their feet, or use &#39;Wreathed In Shadow&#39; to outright subtract from the fellowship archery total. There are, of course, cards that boost your Nazgul&#39;s strength, such as &#39;Dark Whispers&#39;, &#39;Frozen By Fear&#39;, and &#39;Threshold Of Shadow&#39;. But let&#39;s not forget cards that will assist you outside of skirmishes. The most well known of these cards are &#39;Black Breath&#39; and &#39;Blade Tip&#39;. If you haven&#39;t seen these, &#39;Blade Tip&#39; wounds (or adds a burden if on the ring-bearer) the bearer at the beginning of every fellowship phase, while &#39;Black Breath&#39; prevents the bearer from removing wounds (and burdens). That&#39;s just cruelty, and it brings me to my next point: Nazgul are also adept at adding burdens to the ring-bearer. Blade Tip, as mentioned above, will add one per turn when it&#39;s on the ring-bearer. But there&#39;s also &#39;Drawn To Its Power&#39;, &#39;In The Ringwraith&#39;s Wake&#39; and &#39;The Twilight World&#39; to help you on your way to corrupting the ring-bearer. <br>
<br>
Must haves for a Ringwraith deck:<br>
<br>
*The Witch King - he&#39;s as tough as they come, with 12 strength and the fierce trait. Add a Nazgul Sword or Morgul Blade (good for handing out those Blade Tips), or both, to practically turn him into a tank. <br>
*Morgul Gates - plays for free and subtracts 2 from the twilight cost of a Nazgul. Now that&#39;s a bargain!<br>
*Blade Tip - it&#39;s such a nasty card in combination with Black Breath, I&#39;m a bit surprised it&#39;s not unique (knock on wood!). <br>
*Black Breath - see above.<br>
*Ulaire Lemenya - you might be thinking, &quot;Of course I&#39;ll be playing a Nazgul minion in an Nazgul deck,&quot; but what you might not realize is how very useful Lemenya is. Naturally, if you&#39;re playing with Blade Tips and Black Breaths, you&#39;ll want two or three Lemenyas in the deck. He subtracts 2 from the strength of every character bearing a Nazgul condition.<br>
*Wreathed In Shadow - subtracting from the fellowship&#39;s archery total is a good thing, especially if you&#39;ll be exerting any of your Nazgul to use abilities or other cards. <br>
<br>
Well that&#39;s what I&#39;ve got for you. I hope you enjoyed the read and found it as useful as I did. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3035&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
